                <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
                  <table style="min-width:480px;">
                    <thead>
                      <tr class="tab-head-fr">
                        <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">IELTS Band (2nd Language)</th>
                        <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">CLB Level</th>
                        <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">CRS Bonus pts per skill</th>
                        <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">Total Bonus (4 skills)</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr><td>9.0+</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 10+</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>8.0–8.5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 10</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>7.0–7.5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 9</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>6.5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 8</td><td class="pts-cell">3</td><td class="pts-cell">12</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>6.0</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 7</td><td class="pts-cell">3</td><td class="pts-cell">12</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>5.5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 6</td><td class="pts-cell">1</td><td class="pts-cell">4</td></tr>
                      <tr><td>Below 5.5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 5 or below</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
                <p class="tiny muted" style="padding:10px 0 0;">Second language bonus applies only when your first official language is French and second is English, or vice versa. Minimum CLB 5 in all 4 skills to score bonus points.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- CELPIP table -->
            <div class="content">
              <h2 id="celpip-table">CELPIP Score to CRS Points Table 2026</h2>
              <div class="section-label">CELPIP-General only — CELPIP-General LS is NOT accepted</div>
              <p>CELPIP uses a 12-point scale where Level 10 equals CLB 10. CELPIP is only offered in Canada and is available at test centres across Canada. It directly maps to CLB levels, making the conversion straightforward. Register at <a href="https://www.celpip.ca/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CELPIP.ca</a>.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="table-wrap">
              <table>
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>CELPIP Level</th>
                    <th>CLB Level</th>
                    <th>CRS pts/skill (No Spouse)</th>
                    <th>CRS pts/skill (With Spouse)</th>
                    <th>Total (4 skills, No Spouse)</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td>Level 12</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 12</td><td class="pts-cell">34</td><td>32</td><td class="pts-cell">136</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 11</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 11</td><td class="pts-cell">34</td><td>32</td><td class="pts-cell">136</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 10</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 10</td><td class="pts-cell">34</td><td>32</td><td class="pts-cell">136</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 9</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 9</td><td class="pts-cell">31</td><td>29</td><td class="pts-cell">124</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 8</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 8</td><td class="pts-cell">23</td><td>22</td><td class="pts-cell">92</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 7</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 7</td><td class="pts-cell">17</td><td>16</td><td class="pts-cell">68</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 6</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 6</td><td class="pts-cell">9</td><td>8</td><td class="pts-cell">36</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 5</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 5</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td>6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Level 4 or below</td><td class="clb-cell">CLB 4</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td>6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <!-- TEF/TCF table -->
            <div class="content">
              <h2 id="tef-table">TEF Canada &amp; TCF Canada to CRS Points Table 2026</h2>
              <div class="section-label">French language — TEF Canada and TCF Canada are the only accepted French tests</div>
              <p>For francophone candidates or those claiming French as a second official language, TEF Canada or TCF Canada scores convert to NCLC levels, which map directly to the same CRS points as CLB. A French-dominant candidate who achieves NCLC 10+ scores the same 136 CRS points as an English speaker at CLB 10+.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="table-wrap">
              <table>
                <thead>
                  <tr style="background:#1e3a8a;">
                    <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">NCLC Level</th>
                    <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">TEF Canada Score Range</th>
                    <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">TCF Canada Score Range</th>
                    <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">CRS pts/skill (No Spouse)</th>
                    <th style="background:#1e3a8a;">Total CRS (4 skills)</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 10+</td><td>Listening: 316–360 / Speaking: 393–450 / Reading: 263–300 / Writing: 393–450</td><td>Listening: 549–699 / Speaking: 16–20 / Reading: 549–699 / Writing: 16–20</td><td class="pts-cell">34</td><td class="pts-cell">136</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 9</td><td>L: 298–315 / S: 371–392 / R: 248–262 / W: 371–392</td><td>L: 523–548 / S: 14–15 / R: 524–548 / W: 14–15</td><td class="pts-cell">31</td><td class="pts-cell">124</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 8</td><td>L: 280–297 / S: 349–370 / R: 233–247 / W: 349–370</td><td>L: 503–522 / S: 12–13 / R: 499–523 / W: 12–13</td><td class="pts-cell">23</td><td class="pts-cell">92</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 7</td><td>L: 249–279 / S: 310–348 / R: 207–232 / W: 310–348</td><td>L: 458–502 / S: 10–11 / R: 453–498 / W: 10–11</td><td class="pts-cell">17</td><td class="pts-cell">68</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 6</td><td>L: 217–248 / S: 271–309 / R: 181–206 / W: 271–309</td><td>L: 406–457 / S: 7–9 / R: 406–452 / W: 7–9</td><td class="pts-cell">9</td><td class="pts-cell">36</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">NCLC 5</td><td>L: 181–216 / S: 226–270 / R: 151–180 / W: 226–270</td><td>L: 375–405 / S: 6 / R: 375–405 / W: 6</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p class="tiny muted">Source: <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/documents/language-requirements/language-testing.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC official language testing requirements</a>. Always verify current score ranges with the test provider.</p>

            <!-- Bar chart -->
            <div class="clb-bar-chart" id="clb-chart">
              <h4>📊 CRS Language Points by CLB Level — First Language (Without Spouse, Total 4 Skills)</h4>
              <div id="clbBarRows"></div>
              <p class="tiny muted" style="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0;">Maximum: 136 pts (CLB 10+, no spouse). Source: <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/eligibility/criteria-comprehensive-ranking-system/grid.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC CRS Grid</a></p>
            </div>

            <!-- Interactive checker -->
            <section class="checker" id="lang-checker">
              <div class="checker-head">🗣️ CRS Language Points Checker — Enter Your Test Scores</div>
              <div class="checker-body">
                <p style="font-size:14px;color:#4b5563;margin-bottom:14px;">Select your language test and enter your scores for all 4 skills to see your exact CRS language points.</p>
                <div class="checker-form">
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="testType">Language test:</label>
                    <select id="testType" onchange="updateTestLabels()">
                      <option value="ielts">IELTS General Training (English)</option>
                      <option value="celpip">CELPIP-General (English)</option>
                      <option value="tef">TEF Canada / TCF Canada (French)</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="langMarital">Marital status:</label>
                    <select id="langMarital">
                      <option value="single">Single / Divorced / Widowed</option>
                      <option value="spouse">Married / Common-law (spouse coming to Canada)</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="scoreL" id="labelL">Listening score:</label>
                    <input type="number" id="scoreL" placeholder="e.g. 8.0" step="0.5" min="0" max="9" />
                  </div>
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="scoreR" id="labelR">Reading score:</label>
                    <input type="number" id="scoreR" placeholder="e.g. 8.0" step="0.5" min="0" max="9" />
                  </div>
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="scoreW" id="labelW">Writing score:</label>
                    <input type="number" id="scoreW" placeholder="e.g. 7.5" step="0.5" min="0" max="9" />
                  </div>
                  <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="scoreS" id="labelS">Speaking score:</label>
                    <input type="number" id="scoreS" placeholder="e.g. 7.5" step="0.5" min="0" max="9" />
                  </div>
                </div>
                <button onclick="checkLanguage()" class="btn btn-red" style="min-height:44px;width:100%;justify-content:center;font-size:14px;">Check My Language CRS Points →</button>
                <div class="checker-result" id="langResult">
                  <div id="langResultContent"></div>
                  <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/" class="btn btn-red" style="margin-top:12px;width:100%;justify-content:center;font-size:14px;">Calculate Your Full CRS Score →</a>
                </div>
                <p class="tiny muted" style="margin-top:8px;">For your complete CRS score, use the <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/">full CRS Calculator</a> or the dedicated <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/ielts-crs-calculator">IELTS to CRS Calculator</a>.</p>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Second language -->
            <div class="content">
              <h2 id="second-lang">Second Official Language — CRS Points 2026</h2>
              <div class="section-label">Up to 24 additional CRS points for a second official language (French or English)</div>
              <p>If your first official language is English, proving French proficiency at CLB/NCLC 5+ earns bonus CRS points. If your first official language is French, proving English proficiency at CLB 5+ earns the same bonus.</p>
              <p>The second official language bonus is available to all Express Entry candidates and is an underused source of CRS points. A French speaker who achieves CLB 9 English earns 24 bonus CRS points.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="table-wrap">
              <table>
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>CLB Level (2nd Language)</th>
                    <th>CRS Bonus pts per skill</th>
                    <th>Total Bonus (4 skills)</th>
                    <th>IELTS Equivalent (approx)</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">CLB 9 or higher</td><td class="pts-cell">6</td><td class="pts-cell">24</td><td>IELTS 7.0+ per skill</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">CLB 7 or 8</td><td class="pts-cell">3</td><td class="pts-cell">12</td><td>IELTS 6.0–6.5 per skill</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">CLB 5 or 6</td><td class="pts-cell">1</td><td class="pts-cell">4</td><td>IELTS 5.0–5.5 per skill</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="clb-cell">CLB 4 or below</td><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>Below IELTS 5.0</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <div class="info-box green">
              <p><strong>Strategy insight:</strong> If you are an English speaker applying through the FSW or CEC stream, taking TEF Canada and achieving NCLC 9 in all 4 skills earns you <strong>24 extra CRS points</strong>. Many candidates have used this strategy to push their score above the cutoff. See the <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/express-entry-crs-calculator">Express Entry CRS Calculator</a> to model this scenario.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Skill transferability -->
            <div class="content">
              <h2 id="skill-transfer">Skill Transferability Bonus — Language + Education or Work Experience</h2>
              <div class="section-label">Up to 50 additional CRS points when strong language combines with education or experience</div>
              <p>Section B of the CRS awards additional points when high language scores combine with education credentials or work experience. Maximum bonus: 50 CRS points.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="skill-grid">
              <div class="skill-card">
                <h4>🗣️ Language (CLB 9+) + Post-Secondary Edu <span class="pts-badge">Up to 25 pts</span></h4>
                <p>CLB 9+ in all 4 skills + any post-secondary credential = <strong>25 pts</strong>. CLB 7–8 in all 4 skills + post-secondary = <strong>13 pts</strong>. This is the most commonly earned skill transferability bonus — IELTS 7.0+ across all skills qualifies for the full 25 pts. See <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/blog/crs-score-education">CRS education points guide</a>.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="skill-card">
                <h4>🗣️ Language (CLB 7+) + Canadian Work Exp <span class="pts-badge">Up to 25 pts</span></h4>
                <p>CLB 9+ in all 4 skills + 2+ years Canadian NOC 0/A/B experience = <strong>25 pts</strong>. CLB 7–8 + 1 year Canadian work experience = <strong>13 pts</strong>. Use the <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/cec-crs-calculator">CEC CRS Calculator</a> to model your Canadian experience + language bonus.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="skill-card">
                <h4>🗣️ Language (CLB 7+) + Foreign Work Exp <span class="pts-badge">Up to 25 pts</span></h4>
                <p>CLB 9+ in all 4 skills + 3+ years foreign NOC 0/A/B experience = <strong>25 pts</strong>. CLB 7–8 + 1–2 years foreign work experience = <strong>13 pts</strong>. Foreign work experience must be skilled work (NOC Skill Type 0, A, or B).</p>
              </div>
              <div class="skill-card">
                <h4>🏅 French Language Bonus <span class="pts-badge">Up to 50 pts</span></h4>
                <p>From 2023, IRCC introduced additional CRS bonus points for French-proficient candidates: NCLC 7+ in all 4 French skills = <strong>25 pts</strong> bonus. NCLC 7+ French + CLB 4+ English = <strong>50 pts</strong> bonus. This makes fluent francophones with any English proficiency extremely competitive. See the <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/pnp-crs-calculator">PNP Calculator</a> for francophone PNP streams.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="info-box blue">
              <p><strong>Maximum language CRS total:</strong> CLB 10+ first language (136 pts) + CLB 9 second language (24 pts) + skill transferability language bonus (50 pts) = <strong>210 CRS points from language-related factors</strong>. Achieving this requires near-perfect scores in both official languages — but improving your IELTS score from 7.0 to 8.0 alone adds 44 CRS points (68 pts → 136 pts when all skills rise from CLB 9 to CLB 10).</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Strategies -->
            <div class="content">
              <h2 id="strategies">How to Maximise CRS Language Points — 2026 Strategies</h2>

              <h3>1. Achieve CLB 9 in All Four Skills (IELTS 7.0–7.5)</h3>
              <p>Going from CLB 8 to CLB 9 (IELTS 7.0+ in all skills) jumps your score from 92 pts to 124 pts — a 32-point gain. This is the single highest-impact language improvement available to most candidates.</p>

              <h3>2. Aim for CLB 10 (IELTS 8.0+) for Maximum Points</h3>
              <p>CLB 10 earns 136 pts (no spouse) — 12 more than CLB 9. If your current score is CLB 9, targeted practice on your weakest skill (often Writing or Speaking) to reach 8.0 is worth the effort. Use official <a href="https://www.ielts.org/taking-ielts/study-for-ielts" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IELTS practice resources</a>.</p>

              <h3>3. Learn French for the Second Language Bonus</h3>
              <p>Even basic French proficiency at NCLC 5 (TEF Canada) adds 4 CRS bonus points. NCLC 7 adds 12 pts. NCLC 9 adds 24 pts. For English-speaking candidates, learning conversational French and taking TEF Canada is one of the most strategic CRS improvements available.</p>

              <h3>4. Combine High Language Score with Education for Skill Transferability</h3>
              <p>IELTS CLB 9+ combined with any post-secondary credential adds 25 transferability bonus points. If you already have IELTS 7.0+ and a bachelor's degree, you are earning these 25 pts. If not, retaking IELTS to reach 7.0 in all skills unlocks this bonus on top of your core language score increase.</p>

              <h3>5. Consider CELPIP for a Computer-Based Alternative</h3>
              <p>Some candidates find CELPIP easier than IELTS, particularly for Listening and Speaking. Both are equally valid for CRS — choose the test that plays to your strengths. CELPIP offers faster results (8 business days). Register at <a href="https://www.celpip.ca/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CELPIP.ca</a>.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- CTA -->
            <div class="cta-box">
              <h3>Calculate Your Full CRS Score Including Language Points</h3>
              <p>Language is just one of 10+ factors. Use the free CRS Calculator to see your complete score — language, education, age, work experience, and all bonus points.</p>
              <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/" class="btn btn-white">Full CRS Calculator →</a>
              <a href="https://crsscorecalculator.vercel.app/ielts-crs-calculator" class="btn btn-white" style="margin-left:8px;">IELTS to CRS Calculator</a>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="card faq" id="faq" style="margin-top:20px;">
              <div class="card-head">❓ FAQ — CRS Score for Language Test</div>
              <div class="card-body">
                <details open>
                  <summary>What is the maximum CRS score for language?</summary>
                  <p>The maximum core language score is <strong>136 CRS points</strong> (CLB 10+, without spouse) or 128 points (with spouse) for a first official language. A second official language adds up to 24 bonus points. Skill transferability bonuses linked to language add up to 50 additional points. Total language-related maximum: 210 CRS points.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>What IELTS score do I need for maximum CRS language points?</summary>
                  <p>You need <strong>IELTS 8.0 or higher in all four skills</strong> (Listening, Reading, Writing, and Speaking) to reach CLB 10 and earn the maximum 136 CRS language points. This is IELTS General Training only — Academic is not accepted.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>Is IELTS or CELPIP better for Express Entry CRS?</summary>
                  <p>Both IELTS General Training and CELPIP-General are equally accepted and produce identical CRS points at the same CLB level. Choose the test that suits your learning style — CELPIP is fully computer-based and results are faster; IELTS has more practice materials and test centres globally.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>How long are language test results valid for Express Entry?</summary>
                  <p>Language test results are valid for <strong>2 years</strong> from the test date. An expired result cannot be submitted with your Express Entry profile and you must retake the test. Plan your timeline to ensure results are still valid when you submit your profile and receive an ITA.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>How does French improve my CRS score?</summary>
                  <p>French improves your CRS in two ways: (1) as a first official language if French is your primary language (same points as English), and (2) as a second official language bonus worth up to 24 CRS points if your primary language is English. From 2023, IRCC added a French-proficiency bonus of up to 50 pts for candidates with NCLC 7+ in French.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>Can I use both IELTS and TEF Canada for Express Entry?</summary>
                  <p>Yes. You can submit <strong>two language test results</strong> in your Express Entry profile — one as your first official language and one as your second official language. Most English-speaking applicants submit IELTS as their first language test and TEF Canada as their second to earn the 2nd language bonus points.</p>
                </details>
                <details>
                  <summary>What is CLB and how does it relate to IELTS?</summary>
                  <p>CLB (Canadian Language Benchmarks) is Canada's national standard for English language proficiency. IRCC converts all test scores to CLB before awarding CRS points. IELTS 8.0 = CLB 10. IELTS 7.5 (Listening/Reading/Speaking) = CLB 9. IELTS 6.5 = CLB 7–8 (depending on skill). The official CLB-to-IELTS equivalency chart is on the <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/services/immigrate-canada/express-entry/documents/language-requirements/language-testing.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRCC website</a>.</p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>

